title: AP Biology Words That Matter: Explain Biological Processes (Set 3A)
description:
📖AP Biology questions don’t just test content—they test whether you understand what the question is actually asking.

This video targets the Can Do level of mastery by helping you decode command words the AP Bio exam uses when asking you to explain biological processes. Understanding these words improves precision, reduces careless errors, and helps you choose the best answer—not just a plausible one.

If this still feels tricky, that’s okay—you’re building skill, not fluency yet.
Fluency comes from repeated exposure to AP-style questions, not just watching.

In this video, we define five high-frequency AP Biology words using:
- Plain-language definitions
- Clear biological examples
- Real AP exam-style contexts

🧬 Words Covered in This Video
These words appear across all biological systems, including enzymes, neurons, hormones, membranes, and gene expression.

⏱️ Timestamps
0:00 Intro: Why AP Bio Words Matter
0:19 Skill Set 3: Explaining Biological Processes
0:44 Facilitate – Definition + AP Exam Example
1:08 Inhibit – Definition + Neurotransmitter Example
2:01 Regulate – Controlling Amount and Timing
2:54 Maintain – Homeostasis and Stability
3:22 Trigger – Starting a Biological Response
3:56 How to Practice These Words for AP Exam Success
4:20 Closing + What’s Coming Next

🧠 Mastery Focus
Know: Recognize common AP Biology task verbs
Can Do: Translate exam language into plain meaning
Fluency: Quickly interpret what the question wants and respond accurately

📚 How to Practice for Fluency
Understanding these words ≠ exam readiness.
Studying vocabulary ≠ fluency.
Practice with AP-style questions builds fluency.

title: A-Level Biology - Tissue Fluid & Lymph - How They're Formed | Comparison with Blood (2026/27 exams)
description:
⭐️ Check out our website https://www.cognito.org/ ⭐️

*** WHAT'S COVERED ***
1. Formation of tissue fluid
    * How hydrostatic pressure forces plasma out of capillaries at the arterial end
    * The role of oncotic pressure and osmosis in reabsorbing water at the venous end
    * The exchange of nutrients and waste products between blood and body cells
2. Formation and function of lymph
    * How excess tissue fluid drains into the lymphatic system
    * The structure of lymph vessels including valves and reliance on muscle contraction
    * The role of lymph nodes in the immune response and filtering pathogens
3. Comparison of body fluids
    * A side-by-side comparison of blood, tissue fluid, and lymph
    * Differences in composition regarding red blood cells, proteins, solutes, white blood cells, and fatty acids

title: Chapter 13 Excretion and Homeostasis Explained | Biology IGCSE (10 Min Explainer)
description:
Every second, your body is performing a high-stakes balancing act. In this video, we dive deep into Chapter 13 of O-Level Biology to explore the two master systems that keep you alive: 

Excretion and Homeostasis.

Learn how your liver processes toxic waste, how your kidneys filter a "bathtub-full" of blood every day, and how your brain acts as a thermostat to keep everything perfectly steady. Whether you're prepping for exams or just curious about human biology, this explainer breaks it all down with clear visuals and easy-to-understand examples.

What You’ll Learn:
✅ The difference between Excretion and Egestion.
✅ How the Liver performs Deamination.
✅ The "99% Rule" of Kidney reabsorption.
✅ How Nephrons filter your blood.
✅ Negative Feedback Loops: Blood Glucose & Temperature control.
✅ What happens when Homeostasis fails (Type 1 Diabetes).

Timestamps:
[00:00] Intro: The Body's Constant Battle

title: We don't even know what genes are | Philip Ball on biology's biggest mistake
channel_title: The Institute of Art and Ideas
description:
Philip Ball explains what molecular biology got wrong about genetics.

Did we get genetics completely wrong?

With a free trial, you can watch Philip debate the failures of the human genome project at https://iai.tv/video/the-blueprint-for-life?utm_source=YouTube&utm_medium=description

Join leading science journalist Philip Ball in this this exclusive studio interview that challenges some of biology’s most entrenched ideas. Ball argues that familiar ideas - the genome as a blueprint, genes as instructions, proteins as precision machines, even cells as fixed entities - are incomplete or misleading. Instead, he presents life as a multilevel, self-organizing system governed by principles that cut across genes, cells, tissues, and whole organisms, and discusses the radical implications this "new biology" may have for humanity. 

#biology  #evolution  #science #genetics #molecularbiology 

Philip Ball is a renowned British science writer and former editor of Nature, celebrated for uncovering the poetic wonder within hard science. In over thirty books, including Critical Mass (Royal Society Winton Prize), Beyond Weird (Physics World Book of the Year), and How Life Works, he explores how science is deeply entwined with culture, politics, and imagination.

The Institute of Art and Ideas features videos and articles from cutting edge thinkers discussing the ideas that are shaping the world, from metaphysics to string theory, technology to democracy, aesthetics to genetics. title: A-Level Biology - Blood - Red & White Blood Cells | Platelets | Plasma (2026/27 exams)
description:
⭐️ Check out our website https://www.cognito.org/ ⭐️

*** WHAT'S COVERED ***
1. Red Blood Cells (RBCs)
    * Role in transporting oxygen using haemoglobin.
    * Adaptations for function, including the biconcave disc shape and lack of a nucleus.
2. White Blood Cells
    * Function in defending the body against infection.
    * Phagocytes (neutrophils and monocytes) and their role in phagocytosis.
    * Lymphocytes and their role in producing specific responses like antibodies.
3. Platelets
    * Description as small fragments of cells without a nucleus.
    * Function in blood clotting to stop bleeding and prevent entry of microorganisms.
4. Plasma
    * Its role as the liquid component that allows blood to flow.
    * The transport of various substances, including blood cells, nutrients, waste products, hormones, and proteins.

*** EXAM BOARD SPECIFIC INFO ***
AQA - You don't need to know so much detail about the different types of white blood cells
OCR - You don't need to know so much detail about the different types of white blood cells
CIE - Everything is relevant to your course!
